Crypto Wars

Encryption is the highest form of PC security, converting intelligible
data (called cleartext or plaintext among cryptographers) into an
unintelligible form (dubbed ciphertext). Encryption is accomplished
through Boolean mathematics by merging a random sequence of digital bits
(the key) with sequential portions of the cleartext through logical
(Boolean XOR, the exclusive OR) and arithmetic (bit shifting or rotation)
operations. Cleartext recoverability is a factor of the number of
encryption iterations performed and the length of the key. The longer the
encryption takes, the more secure your data. Two forms of encryption are
popularly used: the private (or secret) key and the public key.

Big Brother's Private Key

Private-key cryptography uses one key for both encryption and decryption.
The method relies on a secure transfer of the key from the sender to the
recipient. Anyone possessing the key can decipher the message. The method
used in almost all commercial instances, including most financial
transactions worldwide, is a private-key process defined by the Data
Encryption Standard (DES). This process was developed by the U.S.
National Bureau of Standards.

DES uses a 64-bit key with eight bits used for error control. The
remaining 56-bit key is used for the encryption and decryption. DES
relies on the sheer number of possible keys (70 quadrillion) to keep
encrypted messages secure. In response to recent allegations that DES may
have become unsafe, the government has proposed a new standard called
Skipjack.

Skipjack is an 80-bit, dual-key algorithm developed by the National
Security Agency (NSA). Since 1985, the NSA has been developing a silicon
chip called the Clipper. The Clipper Chip, housed in a tamper-proof
package, is a self-contained CPU containing the Skipjack algorithm.
Designed for incorporation into all future telephonic devices, it will
encode both voice and digital data. The Clinton administration moved to
make this the new standard by stipulating that all new telephonic devices
purchased by the government must have this technology. Therefore, to
communicate with the government, the person at the other end of the line
would need a similarly equipped device.

In the interests of federal crime bureaus, one of several generic
signatures in the Clipper Chip contains a Law Enforcement Access Field
(LEAF), embedded in any transmission. Presumably, removing or altering
the LEAF would be illegal and detecting such a message would trigger an
investigation. Supposedly, privacy would be assured under normal
conditions, but law-enforcement agencies would not be prevented from
gathering evidence of illegal activities.

To make this standard effective, other means of encryption over telephone
lines would have to be prohibited. Naturally, the developers of competing
encryption algorithms, which may or may not be more secure, object to
this trade restraint. Further, civil libertarians object to the
government having a means by which private communication could be
routinely intercepted. There is no obligation, they point out, that
private citizens communicate in a manner that the government can
understand. To combat what they see as the ultimate Orwellian nightmare,
a growing number of computer-literate citizens are banding together to
promote public-key cryptography.

The Public's Key

Public-key cryptography first became popular in 1975 when the idea was
published by Whitfield Diffie. Diffie's method (developed with a Stanford
computer scientist named Martin Hellman) uses a published key to encrypt
and a private key to decrypt. Thus, anyone who knows your public key can
send you a message, but only you can decipher it with your private key.

In 1977, Diffie's scheme was incorporated into a set of algorithms called
RSA (for their MIT authors, Rivest, Shamir, and Adleman). RSA offers
several advantages over DES, not the least of which is that DES was
limited to 64-bit keys, while RSA keys can be any size.

The RSA algorithms currently can also be found in an Internet-published
program called PGP (Pretty Good Privacy), written by Phil Zimmermann. PGP
is still in version 2.0 and has several legal problems, including
unlicensed use of the RSA algorithms and a federal investigation into how
the program found its way out of the country.

Yet another public-encryption scheme that promises to become popular when
it is published is Privacy Enhanced Mail (PEM). PEM will be used on the
Internet and from there should proliferate to most public PC networks.
